<!-- Problem this solves -->
<h2>Why Does Your Room Feel So Flat? The Case for Ambient Lighting</h2>
<p>Plain walls and overhead lighting are functionally fine but atmospherically dead. The moment you turn off the main light in most bedrooms, you're left with darkness or a harsh desk lamp. Galaxy projectors solve this by turning any ceiling or wall into a dynamic light environment.</p>

<div style="overflow-x:auto;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
  <table class="problem-solution-table">
    <thead><tr><th style="width:48%;">The Problem</th><th style="width:52%;">How This Projector Solves It</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Boring flat ceiling with no atmosphere</td><td>Projects a galaxy of rotating stars and nebula clouds across any surface</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hard to adjust lighting without getting up</td><td>App controls color, brightness, rotation speed, and timer from your phone in bed</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cheap projectors look fake and static</td><td>Rotating motor creates realistic star drift — the whole ceiling appears to move slowly</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Smart home setup requires compatible devices</td><td>Works with Alexa and Google Home out of the box after a 2-minute link</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<!-- Supporting questions -->
<div class="supporting-questions">
  <h2>What Does "App-Controlled" Actually Mean for a Star Projector?</h2>
  <p>Most cheap star projectors have one button that cycles through 5–8 preset modes. "App-controlled" means the projector connects to your home Wi-Fi and you get a full interface on your phone: a color wheel with 16 million colors, individual brightness sliders for the star layer and nebula layer, rotation speed control, a countdown timer, and a music sync mode that pulses the colors to audio.</p>
  <p>The remote control is also included for people who don't want to use the app every time. And once it's linked to Alexa or Google Home, you can say "Hey Google, turn on the star projector" without touching anything.</p>

  <h2>Who Should Buy This — and Who Should Skip It?</h2>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
    <table class="decision-table">
      <thead><tr><th style="width:30%;">You Are</th><th>Buy if...</th><th>Skip if...</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Bedroom atmosphere seeker</td><td>You want something that looks genuinely cinematic for under $100</td><td>You already have premium smart lighting (Philips Hue, etc.)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Content creator</td><td>The rotating starfield looks incredible on camera — naturally TikTok-ready</td><td>You need a perfectly static background for long-form video</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Smart home user</td><td>Alexa/Google integration works reliably after initial setup</td><td>You're on 5GHz-only Wi-Fi (this needs 2.4GHz)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Kids' room parent</td><td>LED-safe, calming rotation, auto-off timer makes it a great sleep aid</td><td>You need a laser-sharp, scientifically accurate star map</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>If you need the scientific accuracy of a real planetarium, look at the <strong>Sega Homestar Flux</strong> (~$130). For pure vibe and atmosphere at half the price, this projector wins.</p>
</div>

<!-- How to use -->
<h2>How to Set Up the Galaxy Star Projector in Under 5 Minutes</h2>
<ol style="line-height:2;color:var(--foreground);">
  <li><strong>Plug in and power on</strong> — connect via USB or the included adapter and press the power button.</li>
  <li><strong>Download the companion app</strong> — available on both iOS and Android, free to download.</li>
  <li><strong>Connect to 2.4GHz Wi-Fi</strong> — in the app, tap Add Device and make sure your phone is on 2.4GHz during setup.</li>
  <li><strong>Aim and adjust</strong> — point it at your ceiling or wall. Use the app to pick your color, rotation speed, and brightness.</li>
  <li><strong>Set a timer or link to voice control</strong> — the built-in timer auto-shuts after 1–4 hours.</li>
</ol>

